
Extracts part of a string:

var str = "Hello world!";
var res = str.substr(1, 4);
console.log(res);

// ello

Definition and Usage

The substr() method extracts parts of a string, beginning at the character at the specified position,
and returns the specified number of characters.

Tip: To extract characters from the end of the string, use a negative start number.

Note: The substr() method does not change the original string.

Syntax
string.substr(start,length)

Parameter	Description
start	Required. The position where to start the extraction.
length	Optional. The number of characters to extract. If omitted, it extracts the rest of the string

Return Value:	A new String, containing the extracted part of the text. If length is 0 or negative,
an empty string is returned


                                       Example

Begin the extraction at position 2, and extract the rest of the string:

var str = "Hello world!";
var res = str.substr(2);
The result of res will be:

// llo world!


                                       Example

Extract only the first character:

var str = "Hello world!";
var res = str.substr(0, 1);
The result of res will be:

// H


                                       Example

Extract only the last character:

var str = "Hello world!";
var res = str.substr(-1, 1);
console.log(res);

// !
